Reasoning: The paper discusses the dynamics behind the success of crowdsourcing in the domain of knowledge building, which involves the use of collaborative knowledge building environments (KBE). This topic is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science, including cybernetics (cs.CY), social and information networks (cs.SI), software engineering (cs.SE), human-computer interaction (cs.HC), and computational complexity (cs.CC). However, given the focus on the categorization of users based on their skills and the impact on knowledge building, we believe that cybernetics (cs.CY) and social and information networks (cs.SI) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also involves quantitative analysis, which could be relevant to software engineering (cs.SE) and computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the discussion on the ideal distribution of users for accelerated knowledge building could be relevant to human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
